Obtaining Data

For our project, we are analyzing the correlation between tweet sentiments and cryptocurrency prices, focusing in particular on Bitcoin and Dogecoin.

We imported datasets from Kaggle into our shared Google Drive folder to analyze, so the first step is to initialize the Google Drive plugin and import some packages that we need to import the data.

# Mount drive to access csv files in folder "CIS 233 HW4 Final Project"
# Note: you need to add a shortcut to this folder from your drive if it's shared
from google.colab import drive
drive.mount('/content/drive')

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

Mounted at /content/drive

Bitcoin Tweet Data

Data source: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/alaix14/bitcoin-tweets-20160101-to-20190329

This dataset is really great; it contains a very large selection of tweets that mention bitcoin over the span of several years! Unfortunately, this means that the dataset is extremely large, and does not fit into the memory that Google Colab allocates for us. Because of this, we need to import the data in chunks and do a little bit of data cleaning and filtering at import time so that we can successfuly import it.

tweets_df = pd.DataFrame()
# Import the dataframe in chunks to stay under the memory cap
# Note: this is not a proper CSV. The delimiter is ';'
for chunk in pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CIS 233 HW4 Final Project/tweets.csv",
                        on_bad_lines='skip', sep=';', chunksize=1000000, engine='python',
                        usecols = ['id', 'timestamp', 'replies', 'likes', 'retweets', 'text']):
  chunk.dropna(inplace=True)

  # filter out tweets with very little interaction, because we would expect
  # these to have a very minimal effect on cryptocurrency prices but they make
  # the dataset too large to fit into memory
  chunk = chunk[(chunk['likes'].astype(int) > 0) & (chunk['retweets'].astype(int) > 0)]

  tweets_df = pd.concat([tweets_df, chunk], sort=False)

Because importing this dataset takes several minutes on Colab, write our imported and filtered dataset to a file so that we can re-import it more quickly.

tweets_df.to_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CIS 233 HW4 Final Project/tweets_filtered.csv")

Then, to import the pre-filtered dataset:

tweets_df = pd.read_csv("/content/drive/MyDrive/CIS 233 HW4 Final Project/tweets_filtered.csv", low_memory=False)

Feature Engineering and Data Augmentation (Round 1)

The bitcoin and dogecoin already have most of the features that we want. The one thing we will want, however, is to join the data with the tweet data, so to do this we will convert all of the dates to Date objects, to make it easier to join on.

btc_price_df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(btc_price_df['date']).dt.date.astype('datetime64')
doge_price_df['date'] = pd.to_datetime(doge_price_df['date']).dt.date.astype('datetime64')

The tweets, on the other hand, do not currently contain all of the information that we want to know about them. First, just like with the price data, we want the timestamps to be in the form of Dates:

tweets_df['timestamp'] = pd.to_datetime(tweets_df['timestamp']).dt.date.astype('datetime64')

When we convert the strings to datetimes, however, we need to be careful that we didn't introduce any null values, so let's check again:

tweets_df['timestamp'].isnull().sum()

So it looks like we need to drop null values from the tweet dataset again:

tweets_df.dropna(inplace=True)

The next thing we want is we want to perform sentiment analysis on the tweets. To do this, we used a Python package called Afinn.

from afinn import Afinn

afinn = Afinn(language='en', emoticons=True)
tweets_df['sentiment'] = tweets_df['text'].apply(lambda x: afinn.score(str(x)))
tweets_df.drop(columns=['id', 'text'], inplace=True)

To make this data easier to compare to pricing data, we compute the average sentiment on every day:

tweets_data_groupby_mean = tweets_df.groupby(['timestamp']).mean()
tweets_data_groupby_sum = tweets_df.groupby(['timestamp']).sum()
tweets_data_merged = pd.merge(tweets_data_groupby_mean, tweets_data_groupby_sum, on='timestamp')
tweets_data_merged.reset_index(inplace=True)

tweets_data_cleaned = tweets_data_merged[['timestamp', 'sentiment_x', 'replies_y', 'likes_y', 'retweets_y']]
tweets_data_cleaned = tweets_data_cleaned.rename(columns={'sentiment_x': 'sentiment', 'replies_y': 'replies', 'likes_y': 'likes', 'retweets_y': 'retweets'})

Exploratory Data Analysis (Round 1)

We will graph the data to get a better sense of the change over time, get some sample statistics and examine the correlation between the fields we're interested in.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.dates as mdates

First, let's take a look at the sentiment data:

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1.5,1])
x = all_data['timestamp']
y = all_data['sentiment']
ax.plot(x, y)

ax.xaxis_date()
x_formatter = mdates.DateFormatter('%m/%Y')
ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(x_formatter)
ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.MonthLocator(interval=6))

ax.set_xlabel('Date')
ax.set_ylabel('Sentiment')
ax.set_title('Bitcoin Tweet Sentiment by Day')
plt.show()

Two datapoints that immediately stick out are the extremely positive sentiments in what looks like September and October of 2015, and the extremely negative sentiments in what looks like March of 2018.

From this CoinDesk summary, it seems that there was a continued positive climb in the price of Bitcoin throughout September and October in 2015, which could explain the positive sentiment during this time. Similarly, Bitcoin prices dropped 28% over a few days in early march, which could explain the negative sentiment around March of 2018.

pos_portion = all_data[(all_data['timestamp'] >= '2015-09-01') & (all_data['timestamp'] <= '2015-10-31')]
neg_portion = all_data[(all_data['timestamp'] >= '2018-03-01') & (all_data['timestamp'] <= '2018-04-30')]
pos_max_sent = pos_portion['sentiment'].max()
pos_min_sent = pos_portion['sentiment'].min()
neg_max_sent = neg_portion['sentiment'].max()

There are a couple of interesting patterns that might hint towards the fact that sentiment is related to the price of bitcoin:

  • In early 2018, when Bitcoin hit its peak in our data, there seems to be a small peak in the sentiments as well.
  • In late 2018 and early 2019 when Bitcoin had the massive dip, tweet sentiment actually increased

The second fact is interesting, because it indicates that tweet sentiment might not have a direct correlation with Bitcoin pricing, but instead the sentiment might have some more complicated relationship. This indicates that, though simple correlations may not work, with more advanced machine learning tools we might be able to find connections.

Another thing to note is that, prior to 2017, the data is essentially unreadable because of its low magnitude. This means that, prior to 2017, in its current form the data is essentially unusable input into the model. More generally, Bitcoin prices are variable, with a moving average over time, which makes direct comparison with sentiment data difficult in any form.

To a large degree, our Dogecoin data has similar difficulties to the Bitcoin data. While there are definitely relationships that seem significant, like increasing sentiments in late 2018 and early 2019 at the same time as Dogecoin prices faced a large dip, the lack of a fixed average means that the Dogecoin prices cannot really be compared directly to our sentiments, which are more-or-less stable over time.

These intuitions are backed up by a preliminary spearman correlation, which shows that tweet sentiment is only barely correlated with bitcoin and dogecoin prices, and that this correlation is not statistically significant at the 0.05 threshold.

We were, however, aware of these challenges coming into the projects, and created back-up plans accordingly. To address the issues that were raised when comparing the pricing data to tweet sentiment, we decided to undertake another round of feature engineering and data augmentation, to convert the pricing information into a form which still provides useful insights but is easier to predict.

Feature Engineering and Data Augmentation (Round 2)

We calculate the 10-day rolling average of sentiments and interactions (e.g. replies, likes, retweets) of tweets and take the difference between the current sentiment and the average sentiment of the previous 10 days as the sentiment change. Similarly, we calculate the 10-day rolling average of bitcoin and dogecoin prices, taking the difference between the current closing price and the average price of the next ten days to be the change-in-price feature that our model is going to predict.

all_data_cleaned = all_data.copy()

rolling_window_backwards = 10 # for features
all_data_cleaned['sentiment_rolling'] = all_data_cleaned['sentiment'].rolling(rolling_window_backwards).mean()
all_data_cleaned['replies_rolling'] = all_data_cleaned['replies'].rolling(rolling_window_backwards).mean()
all_data_cleaned['likes_rolling'] = all_data_cleaned['likes'].rolling(rolling_window_backwards).mean()
all_data_cleaned['retweets_rolling'] = all_data_cleaned['retweets'].rolling(rolling_window_backwards).mean()
all_data_cleaned.dropna(inplace=True)

def calculate_change(current_data, rolling_data):
  if current_data == 0:
    return -1.0 if rolling_data > 0 else 0.0
  return (rolling_data - current_data) / current_data

# to standardize data, we're calculating the percent change from the last 10 days to today's data
all_data_cleaned['sentiment_change'] = all_data_cleaned.apply(lambda x : calculate_change(x.sentiment, x.sentiment_rolling), axis=1)
all_data_cleaned['replies_change'] = all_data_cleaned.apply(lambda x : calculate_change(x.replies, x.replies_rolling), axis=1)
all_data_cleaned['likes_change'] = all_data_cleaned.apply(lambda x : calculate_change(x.likes, x.likes_rolling), axis=1)
all_data_cleaned['retweets_change'] = all_data_cleaned.apply(lambda x : calculate_change(x.retweets, x.retweets_rolling), axis=1)

rolling_window_forwards = 10 # for labels
indexer = pd.api.indexers.FixedForwardWindowIndexer(window_size=rolling_window_forwards)
all_data_cleaned['btc_rolling_price'] = all_data_cleaned['btc_close_price'].rolling(window=indexer, min_periods=1).mean()
all_data_cleaned['doge_rolling_price'] = all_data_cleaned['doge_close_price'].rolling(window=indexer, min_periods=1).mean()

all_data_cleaned['btc_classification'] = all_data_cleaned.apply(lambda x : calculate_change(x.btc_close_price, x.btc_rolling_price), axis=1)
all_data_cleaned['doge_classification'] = all_data_cleaned.apply(lambda x : calculate_change(x.doge_close_price, x.doge_rolling_price), axis=1)

columns_to_drop = ['sentiment', 'replies', 'likes', 'retweets', 'sentiment_rolling', \
                   'replies_rolling', 'likes_rolling', 'retweets_rolling', 'btc_close_price', \
                   'doge_close_price', 'btc_rolling_price', 'doge_rolling_price']
all_data_cleaned = all_data_cleaned.drop(columns=columns_to_drop)
all_data_cleaned = all_data_cleaned.reset_index(drop=True)

Exploratory Data Analysis (Round 2)

After the second round of feature augmentation, we want to get a sense of the correlation between sentiment change and coin price change that's calculated based on the rolling window average.

For rolling window candidates from 0, 10, 20, ... 250, we calculated the moving average of that rolling window size for both tweet sentiment and BTC/DOGE prices. Using the Pearson correlation coefficient, we plotted the correlation between the data series over the rolling window candidates.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# correlation analysis with running averages
rolling_window_candidates = [i * 10 for i in range(26)]
btc_corr_rolling = []
doge_corr_rolling = []
for rolling_window in rolling_window_candidates:
  all_data_rolling = all_data.copy()
  if rolling_window > 0:
    all_data_rolling['sentiment_roll'] = all_data_rolling['sentiment'].rolling(rolling_window).mean()
    all_data_rolling['btc_close_price_roll'] = all_data_rolling['btc_close_price'].rolling(rolling_window).mean()
    all_data_rolling['doge_close_price_roll'] = all_data_rolling['doge_close_price'].rolling(rolling_window).mean()
    all_data_rolling.dropna(inplace=True)
  else: # input to rolling window can't be 0
    all_data_rolling['sentiment_roll'] = all_data_rolling['sentiment']
    all_data_rolling['btc_close_price_roll'] = all_data_rolling['btc_close_price']
    all_data_rolling['doge_close_price_roll'] = all_data_rolling['doge_close_price']

  # re-calculating correlation based on rolling window
  btc_sentiment_corr_roll, _ = stats.pearsonr(all_data_rolling['sentiment_roll'], all_data_rolling['btc_close_price_roll'])
  doge_sentiment_corr_roll, _ = stats.pearsonr(all_data_rolling['sentiment_roll'], all_data_rolling['doge_close_price_roll'])
  btc_corr_rolling.append(btc_sentiment_corr_roll)
  doge_corr_rolling.append(doge_sentiment_corr_roll)

# plot correlations between sentiment and crypto price with rolling window
xpoints = np.array(rolling_window_candidates)
ypoints_btc = np.array(btc_corr_rolling)
ypoints_doge = np.array(doge_corr_rolling)

# here we are plotting correlation vs. rolling window for btc, doge.
# initial results show that a rolling window of 100-150 days provides the strongest (albeit negative) correlation
plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.plot(xpoints, ypoints_btc)
plt.gca().set_xlabel("ith rolling window")
plt.gca().set_ylabel("BTC price & sentiment correlation")
plt.show()

plt.gca().invert_yaxis()
plt.plot(xpoints, ypoints_doge)
plt.gca().set_xlabel("ith rolling window")
plt.gca().set_ylabel("DOGE price & sentiment correlation")
plt.show()

We see that the correlation is strongest between the 100th to 150th rolling window, although correlations are all negative.

Data Modeling

From our EDA, we believe we can fit a reasonable regression line to our data, so we decided to use Linear Regression as the baseline model. We use the change in sentiment and interactions with the tweet (e.g. replies, likes, retweets) as features and change in price as the label. We split our data into a training set and a test set using a 75%/25% split, which is standard for machine learning algorithms.

We then use the Random Forest Regression model and compare the root mean square error (RMSE) we get from the two models. We conducted some manual hyperparameter tuning to get optimal results with a max depth of 1000 and 5 estimators.

Bitcoin sentiment + tweet interactions --> Bitcoin Price

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

features = all_data_cleaned[['sentiment_change', 'replies_change', 'likes_change', 'retweets_change']]
labels = all_data_cleaned[['btc_classification']]
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(features, labels, test_size=0.25, shuffle=True)

# run baseline model: linear regression
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

lr_model = LinearRegression().fit(x_train, y_train)
y_pred = lr_model.predict(x_test)

from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

rmse_lr = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred, multioutput='raw_values'))
print('Bitcoin RMSE with linear regression: ' + str(rmse_lr[0]))

Bitcoin RMSE with linear regression: 0.07071483334296776

# run advanced model: random forest regression
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor

rfr_model = RandomForestRegressor(max_depth=1000, n_estimators=5)
rfr_model.fit(x_train, y_train)

y_pred = rfr_model.predict(x_test)

Interpreting Results and/or Visualizations

Results

We were able to fit regression models to our data with a reasonable RMSE, proving that there is some sort of correlation between Bitcoin sentiment and the price of both Bitcoin & Dogecoin. Specifically, the change in sentiment and interactions with tweets, with the change calculated by comparing the current day's values with the average values over the previous 10 days, correlates with the change in price of both Bitcoin and Dogecoin, calculated by comparing the current day's price with the next 10 days' average price. Through this analysis, we were able to determine that a moving average with rolling window between 100-150 days (3-5 months) produced the strongest correlation between sentiment and crypto trends.

With this information, we partially disproved our original hypothesis. Since Dogecoin borrows much of its technical details, and thus much of its community, from Bitcoin, we expected to still see strong correlations between Bitcoin tweet sentiment and Dogecoin prices. Furthermore, because Dogecoin was created as a joke, and is mostly seen as a volatile "meme" cryptocurrency, we expected to see Dogecoin prices to be dominated by sentiment more than more serious cryptocurrency endevours like Bitcoin. It seems, however, that the greater relevence of our dataset to Bitcoin sentiment overrides this effect and causes the dataset to more strongly predict Bitcoin prices than Dogecoin prices. More specifically, the RMSE for the Bitcoin prediction model was consistently lower for forecasting Bitcoin prices than that of Dogecoin for both the linear regression model and the random forest regression model, by a factor of almost 1/2. Furthermore, we learned that the more simplistic linear regression model consistently produced an RMSE approximately 8% lower than the more advanced random forest model. We concluded that forecasting crypto prices is a possible yet difficult challenge, and that using data closest to human emotion as possible along with simple regression models had the highest probability of predicting the right trends in crypto.

Implications and Next Steps

While forecasting crypto prices is a notoriously difficult task using previous pricing data alone, we showed that it's possible to predict trends using a dataset that touches upon human emotion and irrationality: Twitter. Our project results also show that in order to accurately predict how crypto moves in the market, it's more reliable to look at general crypto trends rather than look at high-frequency prices minute-by-minute. Finally, this method to forecast for crypto trends improves with a longer timeline of tweet sentiment on certain cryptos, but that these tweets exhibit indirect effects on other cryptos as well.

We've identified the following next steps for our project:

  1. Perform the same analyses with a Dogecoin tweet sentiment data and see if, all else being equal, Dogecoin prices are more driven by sentiment than Bitcoin prices, as per our initial hypothesis. This will require the (potentially quite expensive) creation of a comprehensive Dogecoin tweet dataset similar to the Bitcoin tweet dataset, as no publicly-available dataset exists with enough tweets to allow for significant machine-learning.
  2. Explore additional sources of sentiment data including Facebook posts, Google search trends, etc.
  3. Conduct additional hyperparameter tuning for our existing models and build data pipelines to automate model training and tuning.
  4. Explore new regression models (neural networks, support vector machines, logistic regression) and quantify their accuracies for predicting future Bitcoin/Dogecoin prices.
  5. Apply these methods to other cryptos including Ethereum, Algorand, and stablecoins and analyze their accuracies in predicting these cryptos.
